Using dependency injection in C# simply means that instead of creating objects directly inside a class, you use another object to create the objects you need. This way, your classes don't have to know or care how their dependencies are created, making them easier to maintain and modify.
Think of it like this: if you were building a house, you wouldn't build the walls, roof, and foundation all at the same time. Instead, you would construct the different parts of the house separately and then put them together later. Dependency injection is like that - it lets you construct your objects separately and then put them together later.
Here's an example of dependency injection in C#:
```
public class Course {
    public IStudentManager studentManager;
    public IExamManager examManager;
    public IAssignmentManager assignmentManager;

    public Course(IStudentManager studentManager, IExamManager examManager, IAssignmentManager assignmentManager) {
        this.studentManager = studentManager;
        this.examManager = examManager;
        this.assignmentManager = assignmentManager;
    }
}
```
In this example, the `Course` class has three dependencies: an `IStudentManager` for managing students, an `IExamManager` for managing exams, and an `IAssignmentManager` for managing assignments. Instead of creating these objects directly inside the `Course` class, we use dependency injection to create them and pass them in as parameters. This way, the `Course` class doesn't know or care how its dependencies are created - it just knows that it has them and can use them.
